---
import Base from '../../hubs/web0/layouts/Base.astro';
import ToolLayout from '../../hubs/web0/components/ToolLayout.astro';
---
<Base
  title="CIDR / Subnet Calculator - network, broadcast, usable hosts | web0.dev"
  description="Calculate the network address, broadcast, host range, netmask, wildcard and host count for any IPv4 CIDR block. Pure math, runs 100% in your browser. Nothing uploaded.">
  <ToolLayout name="CIDR / Subnet Calculator">
    <div class="space-y-6 max-w-2xl">
      <input id="cidr-input" type="text" placeholder="10.0.0.0/16" value="10.0.0.0/16" spellcheck="false"
        class="w-full bg-raised border border-rule rounded px-3 py-2 font-mono text-ink focus:outline-none focus:border-accent" />
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
        <span class="label shrink-0">prefix</span>
        <input id="cidr-prefix" type="range" min="0" max="32" value="16" class="flex-1 accent-accent" aria-label="Prefix length" />
        <span id="cidr-prefix-val" class="label w-10">/16</span>
      </div>
      <div id="cidr-out" class="border-t border-rule"></div>
      <div class="border-t border-rule pt-4 flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:items-center gap-3">
        <span class="label shrink-0">contains IP?</span>
        <input id="cidr-contains-ip" type="text" placeholder="10.0.5.4" spellcheck="false"
          class="bg-raised border border-rule rounded px-3 py-1.5 font-mono text-sm text-ink focus:outline-none focus:border-accent" />
        <span id="cidr-contains-result" class="label"></span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div slot="explainer">
      <p>A CIDR block such as <code>10.0.0.0/16</code> describes a contiguous range of IP
      addresses. The <strong>prefix length</strong> (the number after the slash) is how many
      leading bits are fixed as the network. The remaining bits address hosts. A <code>/24</code>
      fixes 24 bits, leaving 8 for hosts: 256 addresses, 254 usable (the network and broadcast
      addresses are reserved).</p>
      <p class="mt-3"><code>/31</code> and <code>/32</code> are special: per RFC 3021 a <code>/31</code>
      has 2 usable addresses (point-to-point links), and a <code>/32</code> is a single host.
      Everything here is computed locally with bit math. No request leaves your browser.</p>
    </div>
  </ToolLayout>
</Base>
<script>
  import { cidrSection } from '../../hubs/web0/scripts/tools/cidr';
  cidrSection();
</script>
